elements.content: Spiro butadienyl tetraorganocuprates 2a,b were synthesized from butadienyl dilithio reagent and 0.5 equiv of copper­(I) salt. The oxidation reaction of 2a,b with I2 or p-benzoquinone afforded the octatetraenyl organocopper­(I) aggregate 3. This result demonstrated that the butadienyl skeletons rather than the copper­(I) atom were oxidized preferentially. Single-crystal X-ray structural analysis revealed that the high-order organocuprates 2a,b have linear or zigzag polymeric structures, while the hexanuclear octatetraenyl organocopper­(I) aggregate 3 consists of a core Cu6 structure, which forms a regular hexagon.

elements.content: Organocopper­(I) compounds, mainly organocopper­(I) aggregates and organocuprates­(I), have long been attractive both synthetically and structurally. Remarkable progress has been made to reveal the structures of organocopper­(I) aggregates, in which trigonal-, square-, and pentagonal-core Cu n (n = 3–5) structures have been reported. However, their hexanuclear analogues remain less explored, although several copper­(I) hydride and carboxylate complexes are known. On the other hand, as a synthetic strategy, oxidative coupling of organocuprates­(I) has been efficiently utilized to construct C–C or C–heteroatom bonds, via a process in which copper­(III) complexes and organocopper­(I) aggregates are often proposed as key intermediates.

elements.content: Very recently, we reported that spiro biaryl organocuprates­(I) could be oxidized to form their corresponding spiro copper­(III) complexes. Herein we report that spiro butadienyl organocuprates­(I) could also be oxidized but form a hexanuclear octatetraenyl organocopper­(I) aggregate, rather than their corresponding spiro copper­(III) complex. These results demonstrate that, depending on the ligands of organocuprates­(I), either the organic skeletons or the copper­(I) atom can undergo an oxidation reaction. In this particular case, the more electron rich butadienyl skeletons instead of the copper­(I) atom are oxidized preferentially.

elements.content: As shown in , the reaction between dilithio reagent 1 and 0.5 equiv of CuBr·SMe2 was conducted in a solvent mixture of Et2O and THF at −78 °C for 1 h. Then the reaction system was stirred at room temperature for 10 min to give a red solution with precipitates. After the solvents were removed under reduced pressure, the residue was recrystallized in Et2O/THF at −5 °C to afford complexes 2a,b as red crystals in 65% combined isolated yield.

Then the reaction system was stirred at room temperature for 10 min to give a red solution with precipitates. After the solvents were removed under reduced pressure, the residue was recrystallized in Et2O/THF at -5 °C to afford complexes 2a,b as red crystals in 65% combined isolated yield.

elements.content: Treatment of 2a,b with 1.0 equiv of iodide or p-benzoquinone afforded the 1,3,5,7-octatetraenyl hexanuclear organocopper­(I) aggregate 3 as yellow crystals in 30% isolated yield (). When 1.5 equiv of iodide or p-benzoquinone was used, the same yield of 3 was obtained as when 1.0 equiv of oxidants was used, but the isolation of 3 became much easier. Cyclooctatetraenes were formed simultaneously in the reaction, which were detected by GC-MS. Other oxidants, such as CuCl2·TMEDA, hexachloroethane, [Cp2Fe]­[PF6], AgPF6, and 1-fluoropyridinium tetrafluoroborate, were tested, but all afforded little product. In the formation of 3, three new C­(sp2)–C­(sp2) bonds were formed leading to octatetraenyl from the butadienyl units. The above result reveals that the higher HOMO energy of the butadienyl skeleton in comparison to that of the copper­(I) atom would result in the preferential oxidation of electron-rich butadienyl skeletons.

elements.content: 2a,b and 3 are air- and moisture-sensitive crystals and were characterized by 1H and 13C NMR spectra. The molecular structures of 2a,b and 3 were determined by single-crystal X-ray analysis. As shown in a,b, 2a,b are both formed as one-dimensional polymers along the b axis. Due to the difference in LiBr coordination, 2a,b have a linear and zigzag coordination geometries, respectively. In our previous work, the biphenyl spiro copper­(I) complex is free of coordinating LiBr. Only the molecular structure of 2a is discussed here in detail, since the repeating units of 2a,b are almost identical (for the structure of 2b, see the Supporting Information for details). 2a crystallized in the orthorhombic space group Pbca. The repeating unit of 2a consists of one copper atom, two butadienyl skeletons, four lithium cations, and one bromine atom (c). The copper atom was linked with four anionic ipso carbon atoms with a tetrahedral coordination, which was similar to the case for our previously reported biphenyl and styrenyl analogues. The dihedral angle between the two cupracyclopentadienes formed was about 63°. The Cu–Cipso bonds with an average length of 2.011 Å are slightly longer than Cu–C­(sp2) bonds in diarylcuprates (e.g. Ph4Cu2Li2(Et2O)2 1.918 Å). There are three sets of C–Cu–C bond angles ([83.99(13), 84.78(14)°], [106.40(13), 114.08(14)°], and [137.64(12), 139.47(12)°]). Located on the perpendicular directions of the butadienyl skeleton plane oppositely, the lithium atoms are attached with two ipso carbon atoms and one oxygen or one bromine atom. Overall, this is a unique type of contact ion pair high-order tetraorganocupate.

elements.content: Compound 3 crystallized in the monoclinic space group C2/c. As shows, with a C 2 symmetrical axis along Cu1–Cu4, 3 contains six copper­(I) atoms and three octatetraenyl skeletons. The core Cu6 structure approaches a closely regular hexagon. The dihedral angles between two planes (e.g. Cu1Cu2Cu3 and Cu2Cu3Cu4) formed by every three adjacent copper­(I) atoms are 4.069 and 7.190°. Two copper­(I) atoms on each edge of the hexagon are in close proximity (2.3903(5)–2.4092(5) Å), which is indicative of a weak d10–d10 metal–metal interaction. The interior angles of the hexagon are in the range 111.13(2)–129.96(3)°. Every ipso carbon atom bridges two copper­(I) atoms with obtuse bite angles (72.80(10)–74.02(10)°). The average Cu–Cipso bond lengths and C–Cu–C bond angles are 2.009 Å and 168.2°, respectively. Overall, the six ipso carbon atoms (C1, C8, C9, C9′, C8′, C1′) and six copper atoms form a crown structure.

elements.content: The reaction chemistry of compound 3 was primarily demonstrated by its reaction with an excess amount of iodine in THF (). The product 1,8-diiodo-1,3,5,7-octatetraene (4) with an all-cis configuration was formed quantitatively. Such compounds should have a wide potential for further functionalization.

In summary, our results demonstrate that either the organic skeletons or the copper­(I) atom of organocuprates­(I) can undergo an oxidation reaction, which is fundamentally helpful for understanding the mechanism of the oxidation reaction of organocuprates.
